t2m
---

Converts text to morse (raw audio).

Run as:

    $ echo 'Hello, world!' | ./t2m | aplay -r 44100 -f S16_LE

To generate an OGG file:

    $ echo 'Hello, world!' | ./t2m -c 0.8 | oggenc -r -C 1 -o foo.ogg -

    (Capping the volume reduces clipping in the encoded OGG file.)

To morse interactively:

    $ ( stty raw; stty isig; trap 'stty -raw' INT; ./t2m |
        aplay -r 44100 -f S16_LE >/dev/null 2>&1 )

    (Quit using ^C.)


morsetrainer
------------

A learning program, Koch Method. It uses t2m and aplay to generate
sound and ncurses for its user interface. It's best to run it in a
terminal with a big font. The following command also extends $PATH in
case you don't want to install the programs:

    $ xterm -fa 'DejaVu Sans Mono:pixelsize=46' \
        -e bash -c 'PATH=$PATH:~/work/C/morsetools morsetrainer -l 6; read'

This starts the tool in level 6, i.e. 6 different characters. If you're
feeling comfortable, try to increase the level by one. If you're feeling
really comfortable, try to reduce the "grace time": "-g 1.25" is default
which waits for 125% of a character's length after it has been sent. In
reality, there is no grace time ("-g 0"). You can also increase the
number of words per minute. Default is "-w 20".


morsetrainer2
-------------

A learning program for intermediates. "morsetrainer" is meant to teach
you single characters. In time, though, you want to learn to understand
words and sentences. This is where "morsetrainer2" comes in: A series of
characters separated by spaces is sent and you have to write them all
down. This is not an interactive process: You can write them down by
hand and, after the transmission is over, then enter them into your
computer.

If you want to, "morsetrainer2" sends a "CQ CQ CQ" before the actual
transmission starts. This is meant to help you picking up the rhythm.


morsetrainer_linewise*
----------------------

Sooner or later, you will want to listen to longer sequences that
actually make sense. This script reads a line from STDIN and sends it in
Morse. The line will also be echoed on the terminal.

For reading a random part of a german text, the script
"morsetrainer_linewise_german" was added. It automatically selects 30
lines of the text and translates german umlauts into ASCII.


listen_and_repeat
-----------------

This script sends one letter in Morse code, followed by a spoken version
(using espeak).

If called with a "-s" as first argument, it reads lines from stdin,
sends them as morse, and then speaks them.

This is an experimental learning method. Maybe it's better for people
who don't like mixed stimuli: Traditional methods require you to process
audible and visual stimuli, i.e. you have to listen to morse code and
read a letter or word. This script provides you only with audible
stimuli.

Note that you can specify espeak's voice by setting $ESPEAK_LANG. For
example:

    $ echo deutsch | (PATH=$PATH:. ESPEAK_LANG=de ./listen_and_repeat -s)

If you install [0], you can do something like this:

    $ shuf /usr/share/dict/words | (PATH=$PATH:. ./listen_and_repeat -s)

(On Arch Linux, this is the package "words".)

[0]: ftp://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/aspell/dict/0index.html


x11key
------

Creates a simple, black X11 window. Move your mouse pointer into that
window and press the left mouse button. You'll hear a single dit. If
you keep the left mouse button pressed, a series of dits will be played.
If you press the right mouse button (or any button other than the left
one), a similar series of dahs will be played.

This is supposed to be a simulator of a dual-paddle Morse key.

Requires libao, aside from xlib.
